/td>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image108064\" src=\"file:///page4image108064\" style=\"height:15.379593; width:74.201000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>54.3/54 cm</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image109208\" src=\"file:///page4image109208\" style=\"height:15.379593; width:71.366000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>55/55cm</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image110312\" src=\"file:///page4image110312\" style=\"height:15.379593; width:69.098000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>+0.7/1cm</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image111592\" src=\"file:///page4image111592\" style=\"height:15.379501; width:93.085000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>Biceps L/R</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image113016\" src=\"file:///page4image113016\" style=\"height:15.379501; width:74.201000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>34.7/35.1 cm</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image114440\" src=\"file:///page4image114440\" style=\"height:15.379501; width:71.366000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>35/35cm</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td><img alt=\"page4image115824\" src=\"file:///page4image115824\" style=\"height:15.379501; width:69.098000\" />\r\n			<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>+0.3/-0.1cm</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n', 'pilates1-1024x541.jpg', '2019-08-08 10:46:21'),
(77, 'I lost 50kg and saved my life with juicing', 'body', 'body', 'nutrition', 'weight-loss', '', '<p><em><strong>A severely overweight, bulimic with dangerously high blood pressure, 38-year- old Paula&rsquo;s doctor said she was a &lsquo;walking time bomb&rsquo; for a heart attack or stroke. So the feisty Scotswoman turned to juicing and got her life back. Words by Tamara Pitelen.</strong></em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Even when I was three years old, I thought I was fat,&rdquo; says Dubai&nbsp;expat Paula Hughes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;There&rsquo;s a photo of me and my sister when&nbsp;I was three years old. I was in a blue bikini; she was in a red one. I clearly remember what I was thinking as that picture was being taken. I was thinking that I didn&rsquo;t want the photo taken because I looked fat in my bikini.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;My sister was a year older but I grew faster so we looked like twins. Then I overtook her so I was always called &lsquo;the big one&rsquo;. I think you become that self-fulfilling prophecy, you become what people imprint on you.&rdquo; Growing up in a big Scottish family, Paula says she was always overfed. &ldquo;You go back for seconds and then you have Gran&rsquo;s homemade pudding at the end so you stuff&nbsp;your face, clear your plate so you can have pudding. It&rsquo;s all about food; my family is still all about food. It was all homemade cooking, cakes, biscuits and indulgences that people give you as a child.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I would eat until I was literally sick. No one ever stepped in to stop me and I was the kind of child that &lsquo;if you give it to me, fine, I&rsquo;ll eat it till I&rsquo;m ill&rsquo;.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another trigger for a life as a comfort eater came in the lead up to her parents getting divorced. Paula says if her parents were fighting her mum would say, &lsquo;come on girls, get something from the sweetie tin and go to your rooms.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;As a result I now associate things that upset me with sweet foods.&rdquo; A realisation Paula made recently with the help of a psychologist.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FAT GIRL</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even so, Paula says she always had a predisposition to gravitate towards food and excess.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was into food from very young; I always ate more than I should have done. Even with things like a cup of tea, other people would have one sugar; I&rsquo;d have four or five teaspoons. I think it was a rebellious thing.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using food as a weapon soon turned into full-blown eating disorders. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve suffered from bulimia since I was 13 and even thought you have peaks and troughs with it, it&rsquo;s with you for the rest of your life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;At 15, I starved myself in protest with my parents and did obsessive aerobics exercise. I lived on water for a week, it took a friend to say to me, &lsquo;your parents haven&rsquo;t&nbsp;even noticed, just eat for goodness.&rsquo; That was quite a momentous time in my childhood but it was connected to change; my parents had divorced.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Bulimia is a control thing. The only thing you can control is what you eat but to eat a massive amount of food then to purge it is really disgusting when you think about it. It&rsquo;s easy to use food as a weapon but you only hurt yourself.&rdquo;<br />\r\nOne side effect of the bulimia was her teeth rotting away from the stomach acid. Now, her whole upper row of teeth is veneers. By age 23 Paula weighed 135kgs (21 stone) and her dress size was a UK 24-26.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the next 15 years her weight yo- yoed, it peaked at 135 kgs again in her late 20s and for a third time in her early 30s, a year after she first came to Dubai in 2003.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Paula says the pattern was that her weight would increase with life changes, for example, a change in relationship status or moving to a different country. Over the years she tried myriad ways to lose weight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The worst was diet pills that had amphetamine. They were horrific. You got them on prescription in the UK. They said, &lsquo;don&rsquo;t worry about dieting; these pills will increase your metabolism.&rsquo; After three days I couldn&rsquo;t sleep, function or relax, and I didn&rsquo;t lose any weight.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Paula also tried the cabbage soup diet, Slimfast, Weight Watchers, to name but a few. &ldquo;Another one was Obesity Helpline,</p>\r\n\r\n<p>which was powdered drinks of milkshakes and soups and a weigh in every week where you had to urinate on a piece of paper to prove you had ketones in your body and hadn&rsquo;t cheated. I went mental on that. I did lose weight but as soon as you stop, you gain it all back because you haven&rsquo;t dealt with the root problem; you&rsquo;re only addressing the outcome.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It wasn&rsquo;t until Paula changed focus from purely what was going into her mouth&nbsp;to what was going on in her head that she started making progress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IT&rsquo;S ALL IN YOUR HEAD</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;When I started seeing a psychologist I realised my weight isn&rsquo;t just about what I put in my mouth. I spent about two years in that psychologist&rsquo;s clinic sobbing my heart out. Every little detail comes out, warts and all and if you don&rsquo;t let it, there&rsquo;s no point going.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I also tried hypnotherapy and regression therapy, which has so many benefits, that&rsquo;s when I remembered the scene on the beach when I was three and getting my photo taken. I found that photo later and everything clicked into place. So, yes, there have been&nbsp;a few &lsquo;Aha&rsquo; moments of self-awareness, especially in the last two years.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Paula hit her highest weight in Dubai in 2004, she was having a Redbull for breakfast then drinking diet Coke all day at work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Over the years I&rsquo;ve had at least a litre and a half of diet Coke always on my desk. Then I&rsquo;d go out in the evening and drink vodka with diet Coke and eat enough high fat, high carb fast food for four people. It was layer upon layer of body abuse. I was a diet Coke addict. Since then I&rsquo;ve read about aspartame poisoning and toxicity and I look back and think, &lsquo;how am I still alive?&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DO OR DIE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2011, came the body blow from her doctor. &ldquo;She told me, &lsquo;you&rsquo;re a walking time bomb, you could suffer stroke or heart attack at any time.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;My blood pressure was 159 over 99. I wasn&rsquo;t exercising and my diet was high sodium and high fat. My doctor said, &lsquo;you need to go on medication.&rsquo; I was 38 and I knew that if I went on medication, I was charting a course for the rest of my life of more medication. I was sobbing in the doctor&rsquo;s office saying, &lsquo;no, I&rsquo;m not taking medication,&rsquo; she said, &lsquo;you have to, to save your life.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Medication is a slippery slope, you take one type and it has a side effect so you need another pill to tackle the side effects of the first pill and before you know it, you&rsquo;re taking handfuls a day. I don&rsquo;t want to be like that. Plus, the side effects are things like weight gain, headaches, nausea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d also just signed up to do a bootcamp course. The doctor said, &lsquo;you can&rsquo;t do bootcamp with blood pressure like this.&rsquo; So she agreed to take the lowest dose of medication and with the incredible support of her friends, Paula started exercising and changing her eating patterns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;A friend had given me a book on juicing so I made a half-hearted effort. I&rsquo;d drink a couple of juices a day but still eat take-away at night. I was also doing bootcamp though so I lost about 10 kilos in five months.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But then another challenge hit. During what should have been a routine vitamin&nbsp;D injection, the needle accidentally hit a nerve leaving Paula paralysed in her left leg and in severe pain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was at home, completely depressed, couldn&rsquo;t move&hellip; I knew I had to heal this nerve and fix myself from the inside out. That was the start of really getting into juicing and natural foods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I read a book on juicing by Jason Vale that changed everything for me; he talks about what the stuff you&rsquo;re eating and drinking does to your body and why you&rsquo;re addicted to it. He also talks about how the food industry does go out of its way to addict you and keep you weak. Then I booked one of his juicing bootcamp retreats in Turkey and that was where I was reborn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;d get up at 6am, do a meditation or yoga session, then do 45 minutes of exercise like bums and tums or stretching, then have a shot of green super juice, then go on a two hour walk, then come back for the first juice, then there would be a lecture, more juicing, more exercise, some relaxation. I was doing five hours of exercise a day. I lost about five kilograms in a week. It was my first time proper detox and day three was horrendous, I spent the day crying and emotional but&nbsp;on day four I bounced out of bed before the alarm and I honestly felt reborn that day.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DUBAI JUICE LADY</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fast forward a few months and Paula is a juicing convert and 50 kgs lighter than her highest weight. She&rsquo;s alson off the medication and her blood pressure is normal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Juices make me feel wonderful, it&rsquo;s like they switch off the feelings associated with bulimia. When I go off juicing for a while, the danger sign is when I make a coffee&nbsp;with sugar at work, that&rsquo;s a sign I&rsquo;m entering a downward spiral. The combination of caffeine and sugar seem to trigger something.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Juicing is so easy, it fits into my lifestyle and it&rsquo;s led to an interest in raw food so juicing has facilitated this wider knowledge of nutrition. Even if you just have one juice a day, it&rsquo;s an intense nutrient hit. My skin is better and my eyes are clearer. And I can fix all sorts of daily ailments, like water retention. Say you just get off a plane and you&rsquo;re a bit bloated, a juice with fennel, celery, ginger, and pineapple will sort that out; they&rsquo;re a magnet for the nasty stuff and they detox your body.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Juicing, says Paula, has given her back her life as well as given her a life purpose. She&rsquo;s now studying to be a natural juice therapist and wants to make a career out of teaching others about the benefits of juicing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I went to Jason Vale&rsquo;s juicing academy last year and I&rsquo;m doing his natural juice therapist course, that&rsquo;s a self-study certification. It&rsquo;s the only course in the world certified by the Complementary Medical Association. It&rsquo;s heavy going, lots of biology and anatomy but it&rsquo;s the key to my dream of going full time with juicing as a career.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, Paula wants to lose another seven kilos but she thinks part of that process will involve getting back into a psychologist&rsquo;s&nbsp;or hypnotherapist&rsquo;s chair in order to finish dealing with the emotional root causes&nbsp;of her long-term weight issues but she believes that her first-hand experience of the complex causality of severe eating disorders and obesity issues means that she can understand better than anyone the battles of the chronically overweight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;My plans are to help people empower themselves. I want to teach people they don&rsquo;t need pharmaceutical medications to live their life. Traditional doctors have a vital role in medical situations but there are so many conditions where a natural approach can be more successful and of course preventing those conditions in the first place is the best outcome.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FIVE DAY JUICE FAST</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Is juicing really so great? The Awakenings team &ndash; Asma, Tam and Adrian &ndash; gave it the &lsquo;suck it and see test&rsquo;. Here&rsquo;s what happened&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three of us &ndash; a male and two females &ndash; did Jason&rsquo;s Vale&rsquo;s annual Spring Clean five day juice fast, what happened? All three of us lost about 3.5kgs each; all of us were regularly hungry and all of us needed to eat the &ldquo;if you need it&rdquo; banana every day. (Yes Jason Vale, we needed it!)<br />\r\nOn the upside&hellip; obvious benefits besides weight-loss were much improved skin and we&rsquo;ve all maintained an element of juicing into our lives since then. The two of us who used to drink coffee and black tea have stayed off it since doing the fast &ndash; eight weeks at time of writing &ndash; and we feel great for that. As of four weeks later, we&rsquo;d all kept the weight off and Adrian (the male guinea pig) had even lost another two kilos. Six weeks later though, a couple of kilos had crept back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the downside&hellip; Asma suffered headaches through the fast, felt oddly cold and said her teeth<br />\r\nfelt coated. For Tam, a predisposition to candida (thrush) was triggered from all the high-sugar fruit<br />\r\nlike pineapple, apples and banana. We suspect they were also the cause of severe tooth problems for Adrian, which saw him spend five days off work and pay a AED 15,000 dental bill when one of his back teeth cracked right down the middle. Did the juice sugars exacerbate an already weakened tooth? We&rsquo;ll never know but we&rsquo;re highly suspicious and now focus on vegetable juicing as opposed to fruit juices. In summary&hellip; we all have a new love of juicing. It&rsquo;s easy and quick and an effective way to get a big dose of nutrients into your system quick. We all now include juicing in our daily lives but have tweaked the recipes to suite our individual body types and conditions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ANSWERING THE JUICE CRITICS</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Dubai&rsquo;s juice lady Paula Hughes addresses some of the most common criticisms of juicing&hellip;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. But you&rsquo;re losing all the fibre &ndash; you should eat the whole apple not only the juice</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fibre from fruit and vegetables that your body needs are the water soluble microfibres that can be absorbed by our bodies. Juice retains these microfibres and those are the ones that you want. Basically the juicer is doing a lot of the work of your digestive system. When you put fruit and vege in the chute, the machine extracts the nutrients and discards the rest. That&rsquo;s exactly what your digestive system does; extracts the nutrients, the fats, the proteins, etc that it needs to heal and run your body and expels what it doesn&rsquo;t need through the sphincter. Everything that goes into your stomach is broken down into a liquid. That&rsquo;s what takes your body so much time and energy. Juicing gives the body more time and energy and nutrients to go off and fix your skin, your nails, your eyes, your hair, or any health issues you may have.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. What about protein? Do you worry about not getting enough?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No, some of the biggest, most muscular animals on the planet are vegetarians. Plus, it&rsquo;s not about never eat non-juiced food again. Eat steak or salmon if you want just incorporate juicing as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Fast weight loss? Isn&rsquo;t this just a crash diet and the weight will come back?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you go back to the same diet that got you fat in the first place, then yes, you will gain weight back. If you change your diet and lifestyle permanently, weight-loss is sustainable but the&nbsp;final word is that, like anything, there is no cookie cutter answer for everyone. What works wonderfully for one person won&rsquo;t work for another, just give it a try and see for yourself.</p>\r\n', 'carrot-juice-1024x517.jpg', '2019-08-08 10:40:39'),
(78, 'DIY Holistic Detoxing', 'body', 'body', 'nutrition', '', '', '<p><em><strong>How and why to do a holistic detox. Nutrition coach Kaya Peters reveals the latest health trend in Hollywood circles &ndash; do try this at home!&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The word &lsquo;detox&rsquo; is often associated with deprivation, diet and generally forcing&nbsp;yourself to do something that makes you a bit miserable in the hope it&rsquo;ll do you some good. This is far from a durable solution to a healthier body and a better lifestyle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an alternative, Holistic Detoxing focuses on cleansing the physical body and inner organs, releasing mental stress and quieting the mind; a combination that will help regain a state of physical and mental equilibrium.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While in other parts of the world,&nbsp;Holistic Detox is the Next Big Thing, no small thanks to celebrities like Heidi Klum and Elle Macpherson singing the praises of Holistic Detox programmes, the UAE is only now awakening to this trend in wellness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So what does &lsquo;holistic&rsquo; actually mean? It&rsquo;s about focusing on all aspects of our being. Using mostly Eastern teachings as its basis, Holistic Medicine views a person as a whole, rather than just a body with a collection of symptoms. Examples of Holistic Medicine include Traditional Chinese Medicine, Yoga- related teachings and Ayurveda.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where most detox programmes on the&nbsp;market work with fasting methods or drinking juices for several days in a row, Holistic Detoxing is a little different: A programme generally includes eating &lsquo;clean&rsquo; or unprocesed natural, whole foods, which are easy on the digestive system and have additional cleansing value. Examples are steamed vegetables, salads and certain types of fruit. In addition, as much of a special cleansing broth and water can&nbsp;be consumed as needed along with herbal supplements to assist the body in its detox process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CRAVINGS AND BINGES BEGONE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This &lsquo;diet&rsquo; is combined with mild forms of exercise, stretching and breathing techniques, which work on the emotions, as well as getting plenty of rest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So what are the benefits of doing a Holistic Detox? For a start, there&rsquo;s the obvious health benefits of a clean digestive system, rejuvenated liver, new life energy and feeling light and healthy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another major advantage is that because this type of detox does not make you feel hungry or deprived, you&rsquo;re less likely to suffer cravings and over-indulge in processed or junk food before or after starting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>he well-known &lsquo;before diet binge&rsquo;, where you can still eat whatever you want because &lsquo;my diet will start tomorrow&rsquo; is taken away by using several days to prepare yourself for the detox.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In these first few days you cut out specific foods, like red meat, caffeine- based drinks, sugar and more. After the programme, you take the time to slowly go back to a long-term, healthy way of eating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another benefit is the fact that a programme like this can kick-start a weight-loss effort and greatly accelerate weight-loss results. This is because people with a lot of toxicity in their bodies often have a harder time dropping a few kilos than someone who is clean on the inside &ndash; the body protects your organs from these toxins by storing them in fat cells. Toxic fat is stubborn and more difficult to lose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, this type of programme will help you kick your addictions to sugar and carbs; appreciate the taste of simple foods, and help you create new and healthy habits for life. Ok, are you ready to do it? Here&rsquo;s how:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DIY HOME HOLISTIC DETOX</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exclusively for the readers of Awakenings Middle East magazine, Kaya reveals her three-day Home Detox secrets:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To do your own mini detox at home, do the following over the course of three days.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Avoid all caffeinated drinks like coffee and green tea</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid all alcohol</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid all red meat</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid refined grains like white rice, white pasta, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid wheat products</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid dairy, except for live organic yoghurt</li>\r\n	<li>Avoid nuts, except for soaked almonds (soak them for six hours or overnight)</li>\r\n	<li>Focus on eating simple, one-ingredient foods</li>\r\n	<li>Use herbal teas to assist in the cleansing process (dandelion, mint, chamomile, redbush/ rooibos etc)</li>\r\n	<li>Drink three litres of water daily, and add one tablespoon of apple cider vinegar to each litre of water, this will help with liver detoxification.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p>THREE-DAY HOLISTIC DETOX MENU:</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>Wake-up: Two glasses of lukewarm water with the juice of half a squeezed lemon and a pinch of cayenne pepper<br />\r\n	Breakfast: Two green apples, 1 handful of blueberries or other fresh, non-sugary fruits in the morning (any type of berries and occasionally papaya due to its beneficial effects on the digestive system) Snack: 15 almonds pre-soaked in water (six hours or overnight)</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>Lunch: Green salad, raw beetroot, beansprouts, and any other raw vegetable of choice (carrot, capsicum, lettuce, spinach, celery, etc), one cup of cooked quinoa, dressed in olive oil, apple cider vinegar and lemon juice.<br />\r\n	Snack: Raw carrot and celery sticks<br />\r\n	Dinner: Steamed broccoli (as much as you like), one cup of steamed pumpkin, one cup of steamed sweet potato.</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>Do this for three days and then slowly start adding other foods to your diet again, but stay away from anything processed, sugary and refined.</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>For a simple daily detox, just make sure to drink plenty of water, eat green vegetables every day, and have some lemon water in the morning before breakfast.</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>EXERCISE AND MINDFULNESS</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>Because this is a Holistic Detox, it&rsquo;s not just about the food. Over the three days, take time every day for light exercise and a form of meditation. For example, a Hatha yoga class, a Bikram yoga class, a Pilates Core class, or just go for a walk.</p>\r\n\r\n	<p>In addition to moving your body, spend at least&nbsp;10 minutes a day stilling your mind in meditation. This could be mantra chanting (search &lsquo;mantra meditation&rsquo; on YouTube &ndash; there are thousands).<br />\r\n	It could be staring silently at a candle flame; it could be simply watching your breath; it could&nbsp;be putting your iPod earphones in and listening&nbsp;to deep relaxation music like a Tibetan bowl session (again, loads on YouTube). Or you could do a guided meditation such as chakra cleansing either by yourself or at a local healing centre such as Illuminations in JLT. Experiment, search the internet and try something you&rsquo;ve not done before.</p>\r\n\r\n	<p><em><strong>Need some help or want to know more? Kaya offers one-on-one Holistic Detox in the UAE or online. Her programmes are based on the teachings of Traditional Chinese Medicine, Yoga and whole food nutrition. Her seven-day detox works on cleansing the inner organs through the five elements using foods and flavours. Kaya is a certified Yoga teacher and holistic practitioner. Read more on www.kayapeters.com and click the &lsquo;get started&rsquo; tab.&nbsp;</strong></em></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'green-salad1-1024x725.jpg', '2019-07-31 06:11:24');
